The Innovation Fund invests in open-source solutions that are being developed and piloted by Country Offices.
The Fund is looking to invest in emerging technologies that hold significant potential to bring results for
children. These may include blockchain, 3D printing, data, personal/social communications networks,
satellites, wearables and sensors, mobile devices, UAVs, artificial intelligence and renewable energy.

svg.text: What is the role of the country office once the investment is approved?

text.tspan: Once the Country Office receives funding, we ask you to submit real-time data points that show the progress of
the project. Data points include, activity on github, number of users per time period etc.
The Office of Innovation provides support to identify suitable real-time data sources for each project. All projects
and related data are featured on the real-time reporting website of the Fund.

svg.text: Country Offies may receive technical assistance from a global team of experts in the Office of Innovation.
Funding awarded has to be spent within 12 months.

text.tspan: As projects and solutions generate new solutions and lessons learned, we ask you to share your experiences
through unicefstories.org and dedicated networking opportunities with other COs.
Focal points for each project are required to submit 2 reports during the funding period. A report is due after 6
months and after 12 months.

Short Background Note
The Innovation Fund allows UNICEF to quickly assess, fund and scale open-source
solutions that have been developed by companies in new and emerging markets. The
Innovation Fund supports the generation of open source, public goods that address
the most pressing challenges facing children. The Innovation Fund brings together
models of financing and methodologies used by Venture Capital funds and the
principles of UNICEF'S award winning Innovation Unit.
The following set of principles represents a concerted effort by donors to capture the
most important lessons learned by the development community in the
implementation of technology-enabled programs. Having evolved from a previous
set of implementer precepts endorsed by over 300 organizations, these principles
seek to serve as a set of living guidelines that are meant to inform, but not dictate,
the design of technology-enabled development programs.
